<file path="laci-stack-v1.1/README">
# LACI Stack

## Getting Started

### Pre-configuration
Your hosting machine will need at a minumum:

- Be accessible on port 443 from downstream client computers.
- Have a (preferrably wildcard) DNS entry pointing to the system.
  - We have an entry for laci.l3harris.com, and and entry for *.laci.l3harris.com pointing to the external IP of our network.
  - This allows you to route network traefik to apps in authentik via hostnames (api.laci, auth.laci, open-webui.laci, etc...).
  - You can achieve this by manually specifying all DNS entries if needed, it's just easier to get a wildcard SSL cert with a wildcard DNS entry.
- Have a valid SSL Certificate for the above domains.
- Docker and docker-compose installed and enabled.
- Have the laci-stack repo cloned down.
- Have huggingface cache data for whatever model(s) you intend to use pulled on to the machine.
- Have all the needed docker images from the lacichq-docker artifactory repo either accessible or manually pulled in and loaded in to the docker daemon.

### Pulling in Models
Run
```bash
huggingface-cli download <org/model-id>
```
from a machine that can access huggingface, then transfer the contents of your `~/.cache/huggingface/` directory on to your hosting machine.

### Docker Networks
``` bash
sudo docker network create proxy inference
```

### Auth / Proxy
#### Configuartion
```bash
cp web/authentik/.env.example web/authentik/.env
vim web/authentik/.env
# Change any values you need, particularly the secret keys and passwords
```

#### Starting
```bash
cd web/authentik/
sudo docker compose up -d && sudo docker compose logs -f
# Confirm that the container comes up without major issues
```
Configure whatever (federated or not) auth source you will be using (authentik internal user db, LDAP, SAML, etc...)
Check out [this section](https://docs.goauthentik.io/install-config/) to get started, and [this section](https://docs.goauthentik.io/users-sources/sources/) to learn about auth source options.

### vLLM
#### Configuration
```bash
cp inferencing/vllm/.env.example inferencing/vllm/.env
vim inferencing/vllm/.env
# Change any values you need, particularly setting the location you saved your huggingface cache data.

vim inferencing/vllm/docker-compose.yaml
# Choose which model settings you'll be loading
```

#### Starting
```bash
cd inferencing/vllm/
sudo docker compose up -d && sudo docker compose logs -f
# Confirm that the container comes up without major issues
```

#### Testing
Run
```bash
cd inferencing/vllm/
./test-vllm.sh
```
to confirm that vLLM is running correctly.

### LiteLLM
#### Configuration
```bash
cp inferencing/litellm/.env.example inferencing/litellm/.env
vim inferencing/litellm/.env
# Change any values you need

vim inferencing/litellm/litellm-config.yaml
# Choose which model settings you'll be loading
```

#### Starting
```bash
cd inferencing/litellm/
sudo docker compose up -d && sudo docker compose logs -f
# Confirm that the container comes up without major issues
```

#### Testing
Run
```bash
cd inferencing/litellm/
./test-litellm.sh
```
to confirm that Litellm is running correctly.


### Langfuse
#### Configuration
```bash
cp inferencing/langfuse/.env.example inferencing/langfuse/.env
vim inferencing/langfuse/.env
# Change any values you need, particularly the secret keys and passwords
```

#### Starting
```bash
cd inferencing/langfuse/
sudo docker compose up -d && sudo docker compose logs -f
# Confirm that the container comes up without major issues
```

#### Testing
Pull up the langfuse web interface, create account / login, then run the test-litellm.sh script and confirm you see a trace in langfuse.

### Open-webui
#### Configuration
```bash
cp web/open-webui/.env.example web/open-webui/.env
vim web/open-webui/.env
# Change any values you need, particularly the secret keys and passwords
```

#### Starting
```bash
cd web/open-webui/
sudo docker compose up -d && sudo docker compose logs -f
# Confirm that the container comes up without major issues
```

#### Testing
Pull up the webui, log in, configure a model, then start a chat with it and get a response.

### Onyx
#### Configuration
```bash
cp web/onyx/.env.example web/onyx/.env
vim web/onyx/.env
# Change any values you need, particularly the secret keys and passwords
# Set up an oauth provider in Authentik, put the details in the oauth section
```

#### Starting
```bash
cd web/onyx/
sudo docker compose up -d && sudo docker compose logs -f
# Confirm that the container comes up without major issues
```

#### Testing
Pull up the webui, log in, configure a model, then start a chat with it and get a response.


# Important Networking Details

There are two "shared" docker networks used in the LACI stack.

## Proxy
Proxy is a shared network that is used to connect your reverse proxy (Authentik in our case) to all the web frontend containers, so that container names can be used in authentik (`http://open-webui:8080`, `http://litellm:8000`, etc...) for the internal URL. This leverages Docker's internal DNS resolution system to simplify access to the containers. You can still use the host-side port mapping and host IP (`http://<ip address>:3001`, `http://<ip address>:8000`, etc...) if you want, either way will work.

## Inference
Inference is a docker network used to connect the inferencing services (litellm, vllm) to the inferencing API consumers and obeservability tools (open-webui, langfuse) by service name (`http://vllm:8000`, etc...).

# Image Provenance
The [transfer-image-to-chq.sh](./utils/transfer-image-to-chq.sh) script shows how the source images are pushed to the lacichq-docker repo.
Images pulled from laci-\<upstream>-io are from docker.io or ghcr.io, and have not been rebuilt by the LACI team.
Images pulled from laci-docker have been rebuilt by the LACI team to incorporate changes made to streamline usage of upstream apps with the LACI Stack.
</file>

